  "description": {
    "en": "Go beyond list comprehensions — master dict comprehensions, set comprehensions, nested comprehensions, and conditional filtering.",
    "ta": "list comprehensions-ஐ தாண்டி — dict comprehensions, set comprehensions, nested comprehensions, conditional filtering ஆகியவற்றில் தேர்ச்சி பெறுங்கள்."
  },
  "xp_reward": 60,
  "story_variants": {
    "en": "## Vaathiyaar's Assembly Line\n\nVaathiyaar shows a factory assembly line. \"List comprehensions are one conveyor belt. But what if you need to produce dictionaries, sets, or process a grid? Advanced comprehensions are your multi-lane assembly line!\"\n\n### Types of Comprehensions\n\n| Type | Syntax | Output |\n|------|--------|--------|\n| List | `[expr for x in iterable]` | `list` |\n| Dict | `{key: val for x in iterable}` | `dict` |\n| Set | `{expr for x in iterable}` | `set` |\n| Generator | `(expr for x in iterable)` | `generator` |\n\n### Conditional Comprehensions\n\n```python\n# Filter: only include if condition is True\nevens = [x for x in range(10) if x % 2 == 0]\n\n# Transform: if-else in the expression\nlabels = ['even' if x % 2 == 0 else 'odd' for x in range(5)]\n```\n\n> **Key Concept:** The `if` at the END is a filter (skip items). The `if-else` at the START is a transform (change items). Don't confuse them!"
  },
